narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Good review of math concepts I was fairly familiar with.

I learned the basics of precalculus, it set a good foundation of calculus basics: how to use derivatives, interprets graphs, and use logarithms. It was a good introduction to college math courses and the study habits that should be put in place to ensure success.
I developed the skills of starting my work earlier to see what I needed more help on.
This course mostly just sharpened my calculus A skills that I learned in high school.
Aside from the course material, I had to learn how to manage my time and learn independently. The course load was heavy so I had to learn to be very productive.
I learned a lot about Calculus and the ideas that form it. This was my first calculus course so I learned a ton of new concepts.
I learned the basics of calculus and taking derivatives using different methods.
This semester I have gained a deeper understanding of functions, derivatives, and most importantly the applications of such knowledge in a larger context.
knowledge of pre calculus, and how imply in daily basis
I developed a good base for college level calculus.
Other than pre-cal, Ive never taken a calculus class before so this course was definitely an eye opener.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Lecture was sometimes boring, however workshop was usually helpful.

I think that some of the PSETs are too long and do not actually help understand and practice concepts like they will be presented in the exam. In addition, I think that the workshops and office hours can have more purposeful review practices and specific agendas to better understanding of some topics.
A strength is the in person lectures and office hours. A weakness would have to be that the lectures arent recorded if for any reason someone isnt able to make it to class in person.

Some strengths are understanding the problem and helping other students in class. Another one is reaching out to get help when I need it. A weakness is not being patient with the problem sets and giving up too easily on them.

I thought a weakness of this course was failure to review exam-like questions in class. I felt that the level of difficulty of material during classes was not similar to the level of difficulty of problem sets, concept checks and exams. I also felt that some of the problem sets were very long. I thought the strength of this course was the ULAs. They were incredibly helpful. However, I felt that workshops were not helpful at all. They were also too long. Felt like I had three math classes a week instead.

The strengths were that there were many office hours to get extra help with the problem sets and the weaknesses were that the content was taught in a  very abstract way which made it harder to understand than it needed to be.

This course taught me the basics and the foundations of each concept. Through the problem sets, the concept checks, and the workshops I gradually learned how to apply the basics in larger, more complex problems.

A strength would the the availability of the ULA and professor during office hours; I could always get an answer to my question. A weakness would be the fact that everything felt rushed. Sometimes I felt like we spent 20 minutes on a concept that would set the foundations for the filling chapters.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes I would recommend this course because it is a good intro to calculus but I would warn about the workload and express the need to come prepared to class and review topics as the class goes.
I would recommend this course if they havent taken calculus before and would like to start with the fundamentals.

Depends on the situation. If the student needs to take an intro to calculus and knows nothing about calc, then this course would be perfect for them. If they know a little about calculus and don't want to use two semesters with calculus, then math 112 would be better.

I would only recommend this course to students who need a math 112 completion for their major. It is nice to have a whole year to learn the material because calculus has a lot of components. If you have never seen calculus before it will be challenging.
I would not recommend this course to another student if they are just looking for a QR credit. But, I would recommend it if they are looking to learn more about calculus at an introductory level.
I would definitely recommend this course. It helps you set the foundation for future math courses.
Yes, I would recommend this course because you develop a good skill level in calculus.
At first glance I wouldnt simply because of difficulty. Looking back, if I had taken advantage of the ULAs and office hours, I wouldve had a better experience with the course.
